Aug 21, 2024

My fridge died. For the second time in 2 years. After two techs and two "diagnostic fees" I was no closer to a working fridge. With a frustrated wife and 4 hungry kiddos, this needed to get fixed ASAP. I ran to the store and bought 6 bags of ice. Then got to work finding the right one to buy. We found one we liked and bought it at the factory outlet for $500 off of the already $1500 off it was listed at MSRP. I was able to purchase the 3-year extended warranty which I'd never do. I drove the two hours to San Antonio to pick it up. I took the opportunirty to finish an audio book I was reading called 10X is Easier than 2X and started a new one, Buy Back Your Time. While I was there I found a smaller fridge that would be great as a secondary for $300, I couldn't pass up the deal. When I went to put two fridges in my shortbed truck I couldn't close the tailgate. My tie down straps were too short. I had to run 4 blocks to Home Depot and buy new ones. It took me about an hour to make the run, buy the straps, run back, and strap down two refridgerators in the back of my truck with no tailgate up so they wouldn't fall out, in 105 Texas sun beating down. While in San Antonio I thought to call my bestie and grab a quick dinner. I was able to see his apartment and new puppy for the first time, it was amazing. We had a great dinner. On my way home, I called my bestie back and we talked for almost an hour, catching up on all things business and business strategy. I got home around 11:30pm and my wife helped me unload the smaller of the two fridges. We had time to watch a show together and went to sleep.

There's two ways to look at this story, the gap and the gain. 

The gap is...

- My fridge died and was JUST outside warranty
- The manufacturer couldn't find anyone in our area to help us
- All our food spoiled
- I spent $250 and two hours on two technicians that couldn't help 
- We had to spend $2K on a new fridge unexpectedly
- The only option was wait 2 weeks or pick drive 5 hours round trip to pick one up
- I had to buy new tie-down strips
- I spent a lot of time in the car and traffic

The gain is...

- My wife and I had been in a quibble and this snapped us out of it, got us talking, and over it
- We found a new fridge we liked and we had the savings to pay for it
- We saved thousands and got the extended warranty
- I found an amazing deal on a second fridge that I couldn't pass up
- I was able to finish one audiobook and start a new one
- I was able to visit my best friend and see his new place and puppy
- I also followed that up with a great phone call in the car
- I bought some nice new tie down straps
- I jogged for the first time in 4 weeks since a hamgstring injury to the nearest HomeDepot and felt great
- I had a lot of quality me time
- I looked like a hero to my wife and kiddos for "saving the day" and bringing home a new fridge
- I learned my truck can hold two large fridges 

Which do you think helps you achieve and level up and get the most out of life? Living in the gap or living in the gain?!
